.TH SSHPILOT 1 "July 2026" "sshpilot 5.6.6" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
sshpilot \- SSH connection manager with integrated terminal
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B sshpilot
.RI [ OPTIONS ]
.RI [ SSH_DESTINATION... ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B sshPilot
is a GTK4/libadwaita SSH connection manager with an integrated VTE terminal,
port forwarding and tunnelling, and an SFTP file manager. It stores connection
profiles, integrates with the system keyring for credentials, and drives the
native OpenSSH client for every connection.
.PP
When a destination is given on the command line, sshPilot opens it in a
terminal tab using the same forms as OpenSSH (Host alias,
.IR user@host ,
and
.B ssh
options such as
.BR \-p ,
.BR \-i ,
.BR \-J ).
If the destination cannot be parsed, sshPilot prints an error to standard
error, exits with status 255, and does
.B not
start a connection or open a tab (like
.BR ssh (1)).
If the resolved hostname/IP (or username for that host) is not already present
in the SSH config, a successful connect offers to save a new connection.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-\-version
Print the SSH Pilot version and exit.
.TP
.B \-\-verbose
Verbose debug logging (overrides config). There is no
.B \-v
short form, so OpenSSH's own
.B \-v
passes straight through to the connection.
.TP
.B \-\-quiet
Only show warnings and errors (overrides config). Like
.BR \-\-verbose ,
there is no
.B \-q
short form, so OpenSSH's own
.B \-q
passes straight through.
.TP
.B \-\-isolated
Use an isolated SSH configuration.
.TP
.B \-\-sftp
Open the destination in the file manager (SFTP) instead of a terminal tab.
.TP
.B \-\-log\-gtk\-warnings
Also capture lower-severity GTK/GLib info and debug messages.
.TP
.B \-\-fatal\-warnings
Abort on the first GTK/GLib warning or critical, writing a full backtrace to
crash.log.
.TP
.B \-\-diagnostics
Shorthand for \fB\-\-verbose \-\-log\-gtk\-warnings\fR. Recommended when filing
a bug report.
.SH SSH DESTINATION
After sshPilot options, remaining arguments are treated like an
.B ssh
command line. A leading
.B ssh
is optional and prepended when absent, so
.B "sshpilot \-J bastion user@host"
and
.B "sshpilot ssh \-J bastion user@host"
are equivalent. Other remote tools
.RB ( scp ,
.BR sftp ,
.BR rsync ,
.BR ssh\-copy\-id )
are not wrapped and are rejected. Examples:
.PP
.nf
.RS
sshpilot web
sshpilot root@example.com
sshpilot \-p 2222 user@host
sshpilot \-i ~/.ssh/id_ed25519 user@host
sshpilot \-p 2222 \-i ~/.ssh/id_ed25519 \-J bastion user@host
sshpilot ssh \-J bastion user@host
sshpilot \-\-sftp user@host
.RE
.fi
.PP
A bare Host alias that already exists in
.I ~/.ssh/config
opens that saved connection. Otherwise the argv is parsed into connection
fields (via the command converter) and run with OpenSSH in a new tab.
Invalid destinations (for example
.BR scp
arguments) fail on the command line without opening the app session.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I ~/.ssh/config
The OpenSSH client configuration, which sshPilot treats as the source of truth
for per-host settings.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR ssh (1),
.BR ssh_config (5)
.SH AUTHOR
